<p><b>Harold George Belafonte, Jr.</b> (born March 1, 1927) is a <a href="/wiki/Jamaican" title="Jamaican" class="mw-redirect">Jamaican</a> American musician, actor and <a href="/wiki/Social_activist" title="Social activist" class="mw-redirect">social activist</a>. One of the most successful popular singers in history, he was dubbed the "King of <a href="/wiki/Calypso_music" title="Calypso music">Calypso,</a>" a title which he was very reluctant to accept (according to the documentary Calypso Dreams) for popularizing the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean" title="Caribbean">Caribbean</a> musical style with an international audience in the 1950s. Belafonte is perhaps best known for singing the "<a href="/wiki/Banana_Boat_Song" title="Banana Boat Song" class="mw-redirect">Banana Boat Song</a>", with its signature lyric "<i>Day-O</i>". Throughout his career, he has been an advocate for <a href="/wiki/Civil_rights" title="Civil rights" class="mw-redirect">civil rights</a> and <a href="/wiki/Humanitarian" title="Humanitarian" class="mw-redirect">humanitarian</a> causes. He has been a vocal critic of the policies of the <a href="/wiki/George_W._Bush" title="George W. Bush">Bush Administration</a>.</p>
